, Boa, Ghacho Kué; Supplementary Fig. S6). Hence, unless a substantially higher amount of 4He* is retained in the fluid inclusions, ingrowth of 4He* does not fully explain the more radiogenic He isotopes of Cambrian and Neoproterozoic kimberlites (Fig. 2).

In alternative, the high U and Th contents of kimberlite groundmass (1.2–6.1 ppm and 5.2–46 ppm for bulk samples in this study; Supplementary Data 3) provides ample opportunity for implantation of 4He* into olivine (as previously demonstrated for olivines in Jurassic basalts88). The amount (I) of radiogenic 4He* implanted into olivine fluid inclusions from the kimberlite groundmass was calculated using the equation of Dunai and Wijbrans89.2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
